- [Audience Member] When
you showed the cleavage

00:44:56.090 --> 00:44:59.470
of some of the polycistronic
messenger RNAs in E. coli,

00:44:59.470 --> 00:45:01.833
I assume that was an in vitro experiment.

00:45:03.630 --> 00:45:05.610
- No, we've done it both ways.

00:45:05.610 --> 00:45:06.443
- Because it was--
- For--

00:45:06.443 --> 00:45:08.115
- [Audience Member] Pretty inefficient.

00:45:08.115 --> 00:45:10.940
It was only a few percent
of the intact transcript

00:45:10.940 --> 00:45:12.010
that was converted to product.

00:45:12.010 --> 00:45:12.843
So how do you expect there--

00:45:12.843 --> 00:45:15.350
- There are two different slides there.

00:45:15.350 --> 00:45:18.040
One was of several different operons.

00:45:18.040 --> 00:45:20.400
That was done in vivo, okay?

00:45:20.400 --> 00:45:22.560
And then we did the lac operon

00:45:22.560 --> 00:45:24.683
which was done in vitro and in vivo.

00:45:26.060 --> 00:45:27.450
- [Audience Member] But
it's only a few percent

00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:29.973
of the message even in vitro.

00:45:30.910 --> 00:45:32.690
Is it more efficient than vivo,

00:45:32.690 --> 00:45:35.623
the degree of cleavage
of the intact transcript?

00:45:36.900 --> 00:45:38.410
The full-length transcript persisted.

00:45:38.410 --> 00:45:41.180
You know 95% of it was still there after

00:45:41.180 --> 00:45:42.830
you know more than an hour incubation.

00:45:42.830 --> 00:45:43.930
- Well let me put it this way,

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:45.460
with the lac operon,

00:45:45.460 --> 00:45:48.543
we completely destroy part
of the lac operon in vivo.

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:51.150
- Okay?
- So it's more--

00:45:51.150 --> 00:45:53.370
- That was with a model system.

00:45:53.370 --> 00:45:54.690
Now the other,

00:45:54.690 --> 00:45:57.090
so I don't know what you
wanna say about that.

00:45:57.090 --> 00:45:59.300
With the other operons it is true

00:45:59.300 --> 00:46:01.190
that we don't have a good idea

00:46:01.190 --> 00:46:04.996
of the quantitative result
of those experiments.

00:46:04.996 --> 00:46:07.486
- [Audience Member] Okay.

00:46:07.486 --> 00:46:09.490
- [Audience Member] So
does the bacterial protein

00:46:09.490 --> 00:46:13.470
stimulate the RNA of Archaea and so forth.

00:46:13.470 --> 00:46:14.303
In other words,

00:46:14.303 --> 00:46:18.410
if you combine the
different proteins and RNAs

00:46:18.410 --> 00:46:20.083
are the proteins still active?

00:46:21.450 --> 00:46:22.980
- Which protein?

00:46:22.980 --> 00:46:25.580
- [Audience Member] The RNAse P protein.

00:46:25.580 --> 00:46:28.830
So immediately, does the RNAse P protein

00:46:28.830 --> 00:46:30.480
from E. coli for example,

00:46:30.480 --> 00:46:33.140
stimulate the RNA

00:46:33.140 --> 00:46:37.270
of RNAse P from Archaea and so forth?

00:46:37.270 --> 00:46:39.040
- Well if you're talking about experiments

00:46:39.040 --> 00:46:41.590
using an EGS to--

00:46:41.590 --> 00:46:42.990
- [Audience Member] No,
no, this is going back

00:46:42.990 --> 00:46:44.680
to the beginning of your talk.

00:46:44.680 --> 00:46:47.340
- Well just under normal conditions?

00:46:47.340 --> 00:46:48.780
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:51.290
The amount of P protein for RNAse P,

00:46:51.290 --> 00:46:55.630
there are about 400 to
500 copies in the cell.

00:46:55.630 --> 00:46:58.130
And if you try and activate RNAse P

00:46:58.130 --> 00:47:01.360
by attacking the message for the P protein

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:02.850
which we have done,

00:47:02.850 --> 00:47:03.683
it actually takes

00:47:03.683 --> 00:47:06.940
several more hours to kill those bacteria

00:47:06.940 --> 00:47:08.220
than it does for example,

00:47:08.220 --> 00:47:11.930
to just change chloramphenicol
resistance to sensitivity

00:47:11.930 --> 00:47:15.390
because you have to deplete that reservoir

00:47:15.390 --> 00:47:18.620
until you're down to maybe
20 molecules per cell

00:47:18.620 --> 00:47:20.870
which is apparently not enough

00:47:20.870 --> 00:47:22.453
to keep the molecules going.

